      <bioghist id="aspace_f39ed11dea1e8562b553bab1187e9f33">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Imre Reiner, a respected graphic designer, type designer and illustrator, was born in 1900 in Yugoslavia. At an early age his family moved to Romania. At age 15, during World War I, he left home to live independently and attend school for sculpture first in Romania, then in Hungary. In 1920 he moved to Germany, and changed his focus to the graphic arts. In the early 1920s, he traveled frequently in Europe and also visited Chicago and New York. In the late 1920s he started to design typefaces. He became an advisor to the Monotype Corporation in the mid 1930s and made frequent trips to London. In the 1940s he illustrated many books, including editions of Goethe, Rilke, Voltaire and Dickens. In 1950 he became a citizen of Switzerland. Exhibitions of his work were frequent in the late 1940s and early 1950s at such places as the Musée Royal des Beaux-Arts in Antwerp and Museu de Arte in Sao Paolo, as well as at several galleries in the United States. Reiner continued to publish books, illustrate, and have exhibitions internationally until his death in 1987. His typefaces include: Gotika, Symphonia, Matura, Figaro, Reiner Script, Mustang, Bazaar, and London Script.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_dd7776aae6877238035e78630cb3f36f">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection consists of articles and examples of Imre Reiner's designs and a small amount of correspondence collected by graphic designer William Drenttel.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement id="aspace_46dbaea88e5aa037c17978258e488040">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>Organized into four series: I. Art work and designs, 1946-1959. II. Articles, 1946-1975. III. Materials related to Reiner, 1963-1985. IV. Correspondence, 1946-1948, 1998.</p>  
      </arrangement>
